    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Regarding Charles Murray's research on intelligence, why prize this thing, I.Q., so highly? What exactly does it guarantee? Ethical behavior? The choice of socially useful work? Happiness? Wisdom?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Regarding Charles Murray's research on intelligence, why prize this thing, I.Q., so highly? What exactly does it guarantee? Ethical behavior? The choice of socially useful work? Happiness? Wisdom?</p>
        <p>Beyond the level of the individual, is there any reason to think that a more intelligent society would have less internal conflict? Are not those who value their intelligence above all other traits most likely to conclude that their beliefs are right? In that case, intelligence leads to dogmatism, totalitariaism, fanaticsm -- all the isms. And no "ism" goes unopposed by another "ism." CAROLINE MELINE Philadelphia</p>
      </block>
